<div id="review_2874319122" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2874319122" />
    <a title="Linda Kenny" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/43327320-linda-kenny"><img alt="Linda Kenny" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1456240125p2/43327320.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2874319122?book_show_action=true">Jul 24, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Linda Kenny" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Linda Kenny" href="/user/show/43327320-linda-kenny">Linda Kenny</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2874319122" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer6785650926909317918">I don&apos;t suppose this memoir is on too many people&apos;s summer reading list but I became intrigued with Grant after visiting the cottage in New York where he spent the last days of his life finishing this memoir. He was suffering terribly from throat cancer but had hopes that the revenue generated from the sale of this work would support his wife after his death. There is another side story to this that involves Mark Twain who was the book&apos;s publisher and champion (Grant and Twain by Mark Perry). Th</span>
  <span id="freeText6785650926909317918" style="display:none">I don't suppose this memoir is on too many people's summer reading list but I became intrigued with Grant after visiting the cottage in New York where he spent the last days of his life finishing this memoir. He was suffering terribly from throat cancer but had hopes that the revenue generated from the sale of this work would support his wife after his death. There is another side story to this that involves Mark Twain who was the book's publisher and champion (Grant and Twain by Mark Perry). The memoir is very readable even for someone (like me) who knows little about military strategy. Grant refers to the Civil War as the "Great Rebellion" and his perspective as a colonel to his appointment as lieutenant general is frank, sometimes funny and very engaging. Volume 1 starts with his birth through the siege of Vicksburg and Volume 2 continues the story of the war to its end. </span>
  <a data-text-id="6785650926909317918" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


