    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2103906368" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2103906368" />
    <a title="Reid Holkesvik" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/52561750-reid-holkesvik"><img alt="Reid Holkesvik" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1455198485p2/52561750.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2103906368?book_show_action=true">Aug 25, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Reid Holkesvik" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Reid Holkesvik" href="/user/show/52561750-reid-holkesvik">Reid Holkesvik</a>
      </span>

          added it


          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9781542901383" href="/book/show/34529230-the-complete-personal-memoirs-of-ulysses-s-grant">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2103906368" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10595210794274243044">This is a terrific book, a long recognized classic with a wonderful backstory. Completed as he was dying of throat cancer in order to provide financially for his soon-to-be widow and family, this is a record of his early life and most especially of Grant the general during the Civil War. His clear-eyed record and what consistently feels like fair and thoughtful evaluations of fellow commanders on both sides shows what he saw and thought about throughout the war. One has the sense he is writing a</span>
  <span id="freeText10595210794274243044" style="display:none">This is a terrific book, a long recognized classic with a wonderful backstory. Completed as he was dying of throat cancer in order to provide financially for his soon-to-be widow and family, this is a record of his early life and most especially of Grant the general during the Civil War. His clear-eyed record and what consistently feels like fair and thoughtful evaluations of fellow commanders on both sides shows what he saw and thought about throughout the war. One has the sense he is writing about the war for history but has little to prove; he won. He does not talk about his presidency or his life after the war at all. The extensive details of the campaigns may be caviar to Civil War buffs but a bit of a slog for me; what shines through is worth the effort, though. I was struck by his sense of humor, suggestive at times of his friend (and literary agent) Mark Twain, and by his overall sense of the issues involved in the war in terms of military strategy, advantages and disadvantages of each side, strategy necessary for the North to win the war, how close it came to losing, the personal qualities of the commanders on both sides and the importance of those qualities. The relationship between Grant and Sherman I found especially fascinating. Both were minor commanders at the start of the war and rose in importance as they were able to cut through to victories in what was otherwise the bloody stalemate of the war. Sherman learned a lot from Grant, especially the strategic importance of bold offence, improvisation and living off the land. Sherman tried to talk Grant out of these in his plan at Vicksburg, but later admitted he was wrong and depended on these very principles in his march through Georgia. At the same time Grant recognized in Sherman a charismatic, courageous leader who was able to lead his unit of newly arrived volunteers, not yet trained even to load their guns, through the carnage of Shiloh without the panic and despair all around them. I come away with a feeling for the Civil War, the North and the South going in, during and coming out of it, of the Mexican War before it, and of the men involved that is detailed and convincing. I come away liking Grant for his immense practical understanding of war and his humane disgust at the suffering it caused to both sides. After Lee's surrender, he would not let his victorious soldiers cheer and celebrate, and showed obvious delight at seeing the soldiers of North and South quickly getting together, talking and looking up friends on the other side. It was over, thank God, and there were good men on both sides.</span>
  <a data-text-id="10595210794274243044" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


