<div id="review_3205601420" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3205601420" />
    <a title="Ivan Stoner" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/13007727-ivan-stoner"><img alt="Ivan Stoner" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1523231068p2/13007727.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3205601420?book_show_action=true">Mar 26, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Ivan Stoner" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Ivan Stoner" href="/user/show/13007727-ivan-stoner">Ivan Stoner</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3205601420" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer514673203820132344">(A) Reading old memoirs written by interesting people is fun.<br/><br/>(B) Ulysses S. Grant appears to have been a really good person. His end of life reflections are not really of a self-promoting nature, and are much closer to a true and honest assessment of his life. For example he was appalled to have taken part in the Mexican American war, which he viewed as a naked act of the strong taking from the weak. He wrote this book as he was dying of agonizing throat cancer in an effort to provide for his wi</span>
  <span id="freeText514673203820132344" style="display:none">(A) Reading old memoirs written by interesting people is fun.<br /><br />(B) Ulysses S. Grant appears to have been a really good person. His end of life reflections are not really of a self-promoting nature, and are much closer to a true and honest assessment of his life. For example he was appalled to have taken part in the Mexican American war, which he viewed as a naked act of the strong taking from the weak. He wrote this book as he was dying of agonizing throat cancer in an effort to provide for his wife. He refused pain medication to keep a clear head and finished two days before he died. It was a massive best seller and his wife became wealthy as hell. As someone who loves his wife very much, this sort of thing makes me look very favorably upon a person. <br /><br />(C) Man is it satisfying to read about the Union just crushing those idiotic, slave-owning, shameful, self-important traitors. While I feel I'm fortunate to generally not have that weird disease middle-aged white guys get where they read about war all the time, it's hard not feel a little bit of hero worship for the guy who finally figured out how to use the great might of the United States to batter the South into surrender. <br /><br />(D) The middle of this book ends up detailing a lot of military maneuvers ("Sherman was on my right flank, and I sent a messenger to ask him to dig in, etc. etc.") Not everyone's thing. Not my thing. Grant's Vicksburg campaign was apparently a marvel of military logistics and is still studied today. Maybe so. But I can't say I really need to read about its minutiae. <br /><br />(E) Never read much about the Civil War, but I can understand how people get completely obsessed. And I'm very glad to learn that Grant was one of those too-good-of-a-guy-to-be-a-good-president types, and not just a corrupt drunkard as he's often portrayed.</span>
  <a data-text-id="514673203820132344" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


