  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1409423521" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1409423521" />
    <a title="Hans" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1142366-hans"><img alt="Hans" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1292037372p2/1142366.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1409423521?book_show_action=true">Oct 05, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Hans" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Hans" href="/user/show/1142366-hans">Hans</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/26632260-the-personal-memoirs-of-ulysses-s-grant">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1409423521" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer473288927703877724">Humility, that is the ultimate defining characteristic of Ulysses S. Grant. Of all the great Generals through out history he has to be one of the least pretentious leaders ever to hold high command. He did not even like to wear his uniform and was usually mistaken for a lowly staff Officer because of his lack of interest in parading his achievements and rank on his uniform.<br/><br/>Graduating Westpoint 21st out of 39, he was assigned to the 4th Infantry Regiment and later went on to be a Quartermaster du</span>
  <span id="freeText473288927703877724" style="display:none">Humility, that is the ultimate defining characteristic of Ulysses S. Grant. Of all the great Generals through out history he has to be one of the least pretentious leaders ever to hold high command. He did not even like to wear his uniform and was usually mistaken for a lowly staff Officer because of his lack of interest in parading his achievements and rank on his uniform.<br /><br />Graduating Westpoint 21st out of 39, he was assigned to the 4th Infantry Regiment and later went on to be a Quartermaster during the Mexican-American war. Though he seemed completely unremarkable, after the Civil War broke out he continually won battle after battle, inspiring the confidence of the nation. His detractors will argue that he won by sheer numbers and brute force, the reality is more nuanced. Early on he won several engagements where his forces were the ones at the disadvantage and had the Confederates had better leadership could have easily exploited it. <br /><br />What stood out to me through out his memoirs was his extreme Common Sense and Practicality. He didn't care for pomp and circumstance or for shows. He saw he had a job to get done and executed his duties with a clarity of vision and focus to do exactly what was necessary to accomplish his objectives.<br /><br />His humility was also shown by how he tried to avoid wanton bloodshed and his regard for the Confederate Soldiers. The most telling example of this was after the Battle of St. Petersburg when the Confederates were retreating he had his artillery on a prominent hill overlooking their retreat. He could have decimated them in their retreat but he said "My objective is to capture their army not annihilate it".<br /><br />He understood that to win the war he needed to capture the Confederate armies waging the war and cut off and destroy their supplies. He succeeded in both. He also was acutely aware of the role of winning battles and the effects it had in the Political Arena. Knowing that the South had an advantage in a war of Attrition, the North's ability to wage war was dependent on the public support for the War effort, and to keep that support one had to win decisively and bring the war to end as quickly as possible. He knew he was in a race against time and had he failed the History of the United States would have been dramatically different.</span>
  <a data-text-id="473288927703877724" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

